/*
Problem: 34. Find First and Last Position of Element in Sorted Array

Approach:
1. Find the Lower Bound (first index where nums[i] >= target).
2. If the target doesn't exist, return {-1, -1}.
3. Find the Upper Bound (first index where nums[i] > target).
4. The last occurrence is (upperBound - 1).

Time Complexity: O(log n)
Space Complexity: O(1)
*/

class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> searchRange(vector<int>& nums, int target) {

        int n = nums.size();

        int st = 0;
        int end = n - 1;

        int lb = n;
        int ub = n;

        // Find Lower Bound
        while (st <= end) {
            int mid = st + (end - st) / 2;

            if (nums[mid] >= target) {
                lb = mid;
                end = mid - 1;
            } else {
                st = mid + 1;
            }
        }

        // Target not present
        if (lb == n || nums[lb] != target)
            return {-1, -1};

        // Find Upper Bound
        st = 0;
        end = n - 1;

        while (st <= end) {
            int mid = st + (end - st) / 2;

            if (nums[mid] > target) {
                ub = mid;
                end = mid - 1;
            } else {
                st = mid + 1;
            }
        }

        return {lb, ub - 1};
    }
};

/*
==========================================
My Misconceptions / Learnings
==========================================

1. ❌ Wrong Mid Formula

I wrote:
    mid = st + ((st - end) / 2);

Correct:
    mid = st + (end - st) / 2;

Reason:
(st - end) becomes negative, giving an incorrect mid index.

------------------------------------------

2. ❌ Initializing Lower Bound and Upper Bound with -1

I initially wrote:
    int lb = -1;
    int ub = -1;

Correct:
    int lb = n;
    int ub = n;

Why?

Lower Bound = First index where nums[i] >= target.
Upper Bound = First index where nums[i] > target.

If such an index does NOT exist, the correct answer is NOT -1.
It is n (one position past the last element).

Example:

nums = {1,2,3,4}
target = 5

There is no element >= 5.

Lower Bound = 4 (n)

Similarly,

nums = {1,2,3,4}
target = 4

There is no element > 4.

Upper Bound = 4 (n)

This is exactly how C++ STL's lower_bound() and upper_bound() work.

------------------------------------------

3. ❌ Why not use -1?

Consider:

nums = {5,7,7,8,8,10}
target = 10

If ub = -1,

Last Position = ub - 1 = -2 ❌

Correct:

Upper Bound = n = 6

Last Position = 6 - 1 = 5 ✅

------------------------------------------

4. ❌ Why check

if (lb == n || nums[lb] != target)

instead of

if (lb == -1)

Because lb can never remain -1.

If no valid lower bound exists, it remains n.

Also, C++ uses short-circuit evaluation.

If

    lb == n

is true,

then

    nums[lb]

is never accessed.

So there is no out-of-bounds access.

------------------------------------------

5. ✅ Important Concept

Think of index n as an imaginary position just after the last element.

Example:

Index : 0 1 2 3 4
Value : 1 2 3 4
                ^
                n (past-the-end)

Binary Search often returns this position when no valid answer exists.

------------------------------------------

6. ✅ Key Definitions

Lower Bound
= First index where nums[i] >= target

Upper Bound
= First index where nums[i] > target

First Occurrence
= Lower Bound

Last Occurrence
= Upper Bound - 1

------------------------------------------

Possible Optimization:
Instead of writing the binary search twice, create two helper functions:
- lowerBound()
- upperBound()

This makes the code cleaner and reusable. Alternatively, C++ STL provides
lower_bound() and upper_bound(), which implement the same logic in O(log n).
*/
